Hans: Horace meets us, as, in his customary walk, he comes down the Via Sacra. But to-day the poet, usually so cheerful, is in bad humor3 for a disagreeable, persistent man, entirely unknown to him, has intruded himself upon him, wishes to be- come his friend, and asks in a very inquisitive way aster Mae- cenas. Horace has, indeed, already told him that he should not need his company, as he wishes to visit one of his acquaintances on the farther side of the Tiber. But the fib was of no avail, for the new friend will go so far as to let a summons to court be disregarded‚ if he may only accompany the poet.
